#Text=CHAPTER XVIII — A SETTLER IN CLOISTERHAM
#Text=At about this time a stranger appeared in Cloisterham ; a white-haired personage , with black eyebrows .

#Text=Being buttoned up in a tightish blue surtout , with a buff waistcoat and gray trousers , he had something of a military air , but he announced himself at the Crozier ( the orthodox hotel , where he put up with a portmanteau ) as an idle dog who lived upon his means ; and he farther announced that he had a mind to take a lodging in the picturesque old city for a month or two , with a view of settling down there altogether .

#Text=Both announcements were made in the coffee-room of the Crozier , to all whom it might or might not concern , by the stranger as he stood with his back to the empty fireplace , waiting for his fried sole , veal cutlet , and pint of sherry .
#Text=And the waiter ( business being chronically slack at the Crozier ) represented all whom it might or might not concern , and absorbed the whole of the information .
#Text=This gentleman ’s white head was unusually large , and his shock of white hair was unusually thick and ample .

#Text=‘ I suppose , waiter , ’ he said , shaking his shock of hair , as a Newfoundland dog might shake his before sitting down to dinner , ‘ that a fair lodging for a single buffer might be found in these parts , eh ? ’
#Text=The waiter had no doubt of it .
#Text=‘ Something old , ’ said the gentleman .
#Text=‘ Take my hat down for a moment from that peg , will you ?
#Text=No , I do n’t want it ; look into it .
#Text=What do you see written there ? ’
#Text=The waiter read : ‘ Datchery . ’
#Text=‘ Now you know my name , ’ said the gentleman ; ‘ Dick Datchery .
#Text=Hang it up again .
#Text=I was saying something old is what I should prefer , something odd and out of the way ; something venerable , architectural , and inconvenient . ’

#Text=‘ We have a good choice of inconvenient lodgings in the town , sir , I think , ’ replied the waiter , with modest confidence in its resources that way ; ‘ indeed , I have no doubt that we could suit you that far , however particular you might be .
#Text=But a architectural lodging ! ’
#Text=That seemed to trouble the waiter ’s head , and he shook it .
#Text=‘ Anything Cathedraly , now , ’ Mr. Datchery suggested .
#Text=‘ Mr. Tope , ’ said the waiter , brightening , as he rubbed his chin with his hand , ‘ would be the likeliest party to inform in that line . ’
#Text=‘ Who is Mr. Tope ? ’ inquired Dick Datchery .

#Text=The waiter explained that he was the Verger , and that Mrs. Tope had indeed once upon a time let lodgings herself or offered to let them ; but that as nobody had ever taken them , Mrs. Tope ’s window-bill , long a Cloisterham Institution , had disappeared ; probably had tumbled down one day , and never been put up again .
#Text=‘ I ’ll call on Mrs. Tope , ’ said Mr. Datchery , ‘ after dinner . ’
#Text=So when he had done his dinner , he was duly directed to the spot , and sallied out for it .

#Text=But the Crozier being an hotel of a most retiring disposition , and the waiter ’s directions being fatally precise , he soon became bewildered , and went boggling about and about the Cathedral Tower , whenever he could catch a glimpse of it , with a general impression on his mind that Mrs. Tope ’s was somewhere very near it , and that , like the children in the game of hot boiled beans and very good butter , he was warm in his search when he saw the Tower , and cold when he did n’t see it .
#Text=He was getting very cold indeed when he came upon a fragment of burial-ground in which an unhappy sheep was grazing .

#Text=Unhappy , because a hideous small boy was stoning it through the railings , and had already lamed it in one leg , and was much excited by the benevolent sportsmanlike purpose of breaking its other three legs , and bringing it down .
#Text=‘ ’ It ’ im agin ! ’ cried the boy , as the poor creature leaped ; ‘ and made a dint in his wool . ’
#Text=‘ Let him be ! ’ said Mr. Datchery .
#Text=‘ Do n’t you see you have lamed him ? ’
#Text=‘ Yer lie , ’ returned the sportsman .
#Text=‘ ’ E went and lamed isself .
#Text=I see ’ im do it , and I giv ’ ’ im a shy as a Widdy-warning to ’ im not to go a-bruisin ’ ’ is master ’s mutton any more . ’
#Text=‘ Come here . ’
#Text=‘ I wo n’t ; I ’ll come when yer can ketch me . ’
#Text=‘ Stay there then , and show me which is Mr. Tope ’s . ’
#Text=‘ Ow can I stay here and show you which is Topeseses , when Topeseses is t’other side the Kinfreederal , and over the crossings , and round ever so many comers ?
#Text=Stoo-pid !
#Text=Ya-a-ah ! ’
#Text=‘ Show me where it is , and I ’ll give you something . ’
#Text=‘ Come on , then . ’
#Text=This brisk dialogue concluded , the boy led the way , and by-and-by stopped at some distance from an arched passage , pointing .
#Text=‘ Lookie yonder .
#Text=You see that there winder and door ? ’
#Text=‘ That ’s Tope ’s ? ’
#Text=‘ Yer lie ; it ai n’t .
#Text=That ’s Jarsper ’s . ’
#Text=‘ Indeed ? ’ said Mr. Datchery , with a second look of some interest .
#Text=‘ Yes , and I ai n’t a-goin ’ no nearer ’ IM , I tell yer . ’
#Text=‘ Why not ? ’
#Text=‘ ’ Cos I ai n’t a-goin ’ to be lifted off my legs and ’ ave my braces bust and be choked ; not if I knows it , and not by ‘ Im .
#Text=Wait till I set a jolly good flint a-flyin ’ at the back o ’ ’ is jolly old ’ ed some day !
#Text=Now look t’other side the harch ; not the side where Jarsper ’s door is ; t’other side . ’
#Text=‘ I see . ’
#Text=‘ A little way in , o ’ that side , there ’s a low door , down two steps .
#Text=That ’s Topeseses with ’ is name on a hoval plate . ’
